"230":{"department":"PHYSICS","number":"230","title":"Quantum Mechanics","description":"Fundamental concepts. Introduction to Hilbert spaces and Dirac's notation. Postulates applied to simple systems, including those with periodic structure. Symmetry operations and gauge transformation. The path integral formulation of quantum statistical mechanics. Problems related to measurement theory. The quantum theory of angular momenta and central potential problems. Prerequisite: PHYSICS 131 or equivalent.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":122718,"primary":[[],[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"11:00:00 AM","end":"12:15:00 PM","location":"200-107"}],"id":17757}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"231":{"department":"PHYSICS","number":"231","title":"Quantum Mechanics","description":"Basis for higher level courses on atomic solid state and particle physics.  Problems related to measurement theory and introduction to quantum computing.  Approximation methods for time-independent and time-dependent perturbations. Semiclassical and quantum theory of radiation, second quantization of radiation and matter fields. Systems of identical particles and many electron atoms and molecules. Prerequisite: PHYSICS 230.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":122719,"primary":[[],[],[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"11:00:00 AM","end":"12:15:00 PM","location":"Hewlett Teaching Center 103"}],"id":18028}]],"primary_type":"Lecture","secondary":[[],[],[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"5:00:00 PM","end":"6:00:00 PM","location":""}],"id":18596}]],"secondary_type":"Discussion"},
"234":{"department":"PHYSICS","number":"234","title":"Advanced Topics in Quantum Mechanics (PHYSICS 134)","description":"Scattering theory, partial wave expansion, Born approximation. Additional topics may include nature of quantum measurement, EPR paradox, Bell's inequality, and topics in quantum information science; path integrals and applications; Berry's phase; structure of multi-electron atoms (Hartree-Fock); relativistic quantum mechanics (Dirac equation). Undergraduates register for PHYSICS 134 (4 units). Graduate students register for PHYSICS 234 (3 units); graduate students required to complete additional assignments in a format determined by the instructor. Prerequisites: PHYSICS 130, PHYSICS 131.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":200264,"primary":[[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"11:00:00 AM","end":"12:30:00 PM","location":"Hewlett Teaching Center 102"}],"id":27762}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
